<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-07-17T20:41:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-07-17T20:41:00-05:00" n="1534" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1534">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.51/58.</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">Vice Consul <persName type="from">Silliman</persName> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss>.</hi><note n="142" xml:id="d1534fn142">Communicated to the French Chargé d’Affaires July 18,
                                    1914.</note>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="italic">Saltillo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-07-17T19:00:00-06:41">
                                        <hi rend="italic">July 17, 1914, 7 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Your July 16, 5 p.m. General Natera, Governor of Zacatecas, at
                                present in Monterey. Will take the matter up with him personally
                                to-morrow. There are twelve French Christian authorities [sic]
                                remaining here. They received rough treatment when Saltillo was
                                occupied but are safe and unmolested. Was assured by local
                                government this afternoon that subject to certain restrictions they
                                will receive full protection.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Silliman</hi></signed>.</closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>